T1  - Coerced Practice Implementation in Cases of Low Cultural Fit: Cultural Change and Practice Adaptation During the Implementation of Six Sigma at 3M
AU  - Canato, Anna
AU  - Ravasi, Davide
AU  - Phillips, Nelson
Y1  - 2013/03/05
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.0093
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2011.0093
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1724
EP  - 1753
VL  - 56
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article, we present the findings of a longitudinal study of coerced implementation of a practice in the face of a low degree of fit between the practice and an organization's culture. Contrary to current predictions stating that a lack of cultural fit will eventually be resolved through adaptation of new practices, our findings portray the implementation of culturally dissonant practices as an ongoing process involving the mutual adaptation of organizational practices and culture. Our emerging model describes the cultural changes induced by the coercive implementation of new practices as involving a partial change in shared beliefs and behavioral patterns and a more general enrichment of the cultural repertoire of organization members.
AB  - In this article, we present the findings of a longitudinal study of coerced implementation of a practice in the face of a low degree of fit between the practice and an organization's culture. Contrary to current predictions stating that a lack of cultural fit will eventually be resolved through adaptation of new practices, our findings portray the implementation of culturally dissonant practices as an ongoing process involving the mutual adaptation of organizational practices and culture. Our emerging model describes the cultural changes induced by the coercive implementation of new practices as involving a partial change in shared beliefs and behavioral patterns and a more general enrichment of the cultural repertoire of organization members.
